revision.text:
{{italic title}} [[Image:BernPhysiologusFol12v.jpg|thumb|Folio 12v of the Bern Physiologus.]] The '''''Bern Physiologus''''' (Bern, [[Burgerbibliothek of Berne|Burgerbibliothek]], ''Codex Bongarsianus'' 318) is a 9th-century [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] copy of the [[Latin language|Latin]] translation of the ''[[Physiologus]]''. It was probably produced at [[Reims]] about 825-850. It is believed to be a copy of a 5th-century manuscript. Many of its miniatures are set, unframed, into the text block, which was a characteristic of late-antique manuscripts. It is one of the oldest extant illustrated copies of the ''Physiologus''.
==References== *{{Cite book|first=Robert G. |last=Calkins |title=Illuminated books of the Middle Ages |publisher=[[Cornell University Press]] |location=[[Ithaca, New York]] |year=1983 |pages= |isbn=0-8014-1506-3 |oclc=9394443}}{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}
