'''Contact guidance''' refers to a phenomenon for which the orientation of cells and [[stress fiber]]s is influenced by geometrical patterns such as nano/microgrooves on substrates, or collagen fibers in gels and soft tissues.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wang|first1=J. H.|last2=Grood|first2=E. S.|title=The strain magnitude and contact guidance determine orientation response of fibroblasts to cyclic substrate strains|journal=Connective Tissue Research|date=1 January 2000|volume=41|issue=1|pages=29–36|pmid=10826706|issn=0300-8207|doi=10.3109/03008200009005639}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Provenzano|first1=Paolo P.|last2=Inman|first2=David R.|last3=Eliceiri|first3=Kevin W.|last4=Trier|first4=Steven M.|last5=Keely|first5=Patricia J.|title=Contact Guidance Mediated Three-Dimensional Cell Migration is Regulated by Rho/ROCK-Dependent Matrix Reorganization|journal=Biophysical Journal|volume=95|issue=11|pages=5374–5384|doi=10.1529/biophysj.108.133116|pmid=18775961|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1529/biophysj.108.133116|year=2008|bibcode=2008BpJ....95.5374P|pmc=2586586}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=de Jonge|first1=Nicky|last2=Kanters|first2=Frans M. W.|last3=Baaijens|first3=Frank P. T.|last4=Bouten|first4=Carlijn V.C. |author-link4=Carlijn Bouten|title=Strain-induced Collagen Organization at the Micro-level in Fibrin-based Engineered Tissue Constructs|journal=Annals of Biomedical Engineering|date=27 November 2012|volume=41|issue=4|pages=763–774|doi=10.1007/s10439-012-0704-3|pmid=23184346}}</ref> This phenomenon was discovered in 1912,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Harrison|first1=Ross Granville|title=The cultivation of tissues in extraneous media as a method of morphogenetic study|journal=The Anatomical Record|date=1912|volume=6|pages=181–193|doi=10.1002/ar.1090060404}}</ref> and the terminology was introduced in 1945,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Weiss|first1=Paul|title=Experiments on cell and axon orientation in vitro: The role of colloidal exudates in tissue organization|journal=Journal of Experimental Zoology|date=December 1945|volume=100|issue=3|pages=353–386|doi=10.1002/jez.1401000305}}</ref> but it is with the development of tissue engineering{{when|date=November 2016}} that researchers drew increasing attention on this topic, seeing the potential of contact guidance in influencing the morphology and organization of cells. Nevertheless, the biological processes underlying contact guidance are still unclear.

==Contact guidance on two-dimensional substrates==
When cells are seeded onto flat substrates, they generally exhibit a random orientation.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=LOESBERG|first1=W|last2=TERIET|first2=J|last3=VANDELFT|first3=F|last4=SCHON|first4=P|last5=FIGDOR|first5=C|last6=SPELLER|first6=S|last7=VANLOON|first7=J|last8=WALBOOMERS|first8=X|last9=JANSEN|first9=J|title=The threshold at which substrate nanogroove dimensions may influence fibroblast alignment and adhesion|journal=Biomaterials|date=September 2007|volume=28|issue=27|pages=3944–3951|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2007.05.030|pmid=17576010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lamers|first1=Edwin|last2=Frank Walboomers|first2=X.|last3=Domanski|first3=Maciej|last4=te Riet|first4=Joost|last5=van Delft|first5=Falco C.M.J.M.|last6=Luttge|first6=Regina|last7=Winnubst|first7=Louis A.J.A.|last8=Gardeniers|first8=Han J.G.E.|last9=Jansen|first9=John A.|title=The influence of nanoscale grooved substrates on osteoblast behavior and extracellular matrix deposition|journal=Biomaterials|date=April 2010|volume=31|issue=12|pages=3307–3316|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2010.01.034|pmid=20122723}}</ref> Conversely, when substrates have topographical patterns, the orientation of cells cultured on these surfaces is influenced by these geometrical cues. For example, if a substrate has nano/microgrooves running parallel to each other, cells orient along the direction of these topographical patterns.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lamers|first1=Edwin|last2=Frank Walboomers|first2=X.|last3=Domanski|first3=Maciej|last4=te Riet|first4=Joost|last5=van Delft|first5=Falco C.M.J.M.|last6=Luttge|first6=Regina|last7=Winnubst|first7=Louis A.J.A.|last8=Gardeniers|first8=Han J.G.E.|last9=Jansen|first9=John A.|title=The influence of nanoscale grooved substrates on osteoblast behavior and extracellular matrix deposition|journal=Biomaterials|date=April 2010|volume=31|issue=12|pages=3307–3316|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2010.01.034|pmid=20122723}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=den Braber|first1=E.T.|last2=de Ruijter|first2=J.E.|last3=Smits|first3=H.T.J.|last4=Ginsel|first4=L.A.|last5=von Recum|first5=A.F.|last6=Jansen|first6=J.A.|title=Quantitative analysis of cell proliferation and orientation on substrata with uniform parallel surface micro-grooves|journal=Biomaterials|date=June 1996|volume=17|issue=11|pages=1093–1099|doi=10.1016/0142-9612(96)85910-2|pmid=8718969}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Walboomers|first1=X. F.|last2=Monaghan|first2=W.|last3=Curtis|first3=A. S. G.|last4=Jansen|first4=J. A.|title=Attachment of fibroblasts on smooth and microgrooved polystyrene|journal=Journal of Biomedical Materials Research|date=August 1999|volume=46|issue=2|pages=212–220|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-4636(199908)46:2<212::AID-JBM10>3.0.CO;2-Y|pmid=10379999}}</ref> Therefore, cells seem to be able to sense the morphological characteristics of their surrounding and consequently respond by adopting the orientation of topographical stimuli. A similar effect can be obtained when cells are cultured on flat surfaces with lines of proteins printed on top (to which cells can adhere), interspersed by repellent lines; also in that case, cells align along the patterns.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zimerman|first1=B.|last2=Arnold|first2=M.|last3=Ulmer|first3=J.|last4=Blümmel|first4=J.|last5=Besser|first5=A.|last6=Spatz|first6=J.P.|last7=Geiger|first7=B.|title=Formation of focal adhesion-stress fibre complexes coordinated by adhesive and non-adhesive surface domains|journal=IEE Proceedings - Nanobiotechnology|date=2004|volume=151|issue=2|pages=62|doi=10.1049/ip-nbt:20040474}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Alford|first1=Patrick W.|last2=Nesmith|first2=Alexander P.|last3=Seywerd|first3=Johannes N.|last4=Grosberg|first4=Anna|last5=Parker|first5=Kevin Kit|title=Vascular smooth muscle contractility depends on cell shape|journal=Integrative Biology|date=2011|volume=3|issue=11|pages=1063|doi=10.1039/c1ib00061f}}</ref>
It has been observed that the phenomenon of contact guidance on microgrooved surfaces is influenced by the groove width. For instance, osteoblast-like cells align along the nanogrooves only for grooves wider than 75&nbsp;nm.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lamers|first1=Edwin|last2=Frank Walboomers|first2=X.|last3=Domanski|first3=Maciej|last4=te Riet|first4=Joost|last5=van Delft|first5=Falco C.M.J.M.|last6=Luttge|first6=Regina|last7=Winnubst|first7=Louis A.J.A.|last8=Gardeniers|first8=Han J.G.E.|last9=Jansen|first9=John A.|title=The influence of nanoscale grooved substrates on osteoblast behavior and extracellular matrix deposition|journal=Biomaterials|date=April 2010|volume=31|issue=12|pages=3307–3316|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2010.01.034|pmid=20122723}}</ref> A similar behavior has been observed with other cell types, such as fibroblasts, which align along these topographical patterns when the grooves are wider than 150&nbsp;nm.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=LOESBERG|first1=W|last2=TERIET|first2=J|last3=VANDELFT|first3=F|last4=SCHON|first4=P|last5=FIGDOR|first5=C|last6=SPELLER|first6=S|last7=VANLOON|first7=J|last8=WALBOOMERS|first8=X|last9=JANSEN|first9=J|title=The threshold at which substrate nanogroove dimensions may influence fibroblast alignment and adhesion|journal=Biomaterials|date=September 2007|volume=28|issue=27|pages=3944–3951|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2007.05.030|pmid=17576010}}</ref> On the other hand, too large values of groove widths can also decrease the effects of contact guidance <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Charest|first1=Joseph L.|last2=García|first2=Andrés J.|last3=King|first3=William P.|title=Myoblast alignment and differentiation on cell culture substrates with microscale topography and model chemistries|journal=Biomaterials|volume=28|issue=13|pages=2202–2210|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2007.01.020|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.biomaterials.2007.01.020|pmid=17267031}}</ref>

==Contact guidance in three-dimensional structures==
Cells can orient in response to contact guidance also when located inside three-dimensional structures, such as collagen gels, scaffolds, and soft tissues. For those conditions, it has been demonstrated that the geometrical cues provided by collagen or scaffold fibers are able to influence the orientation of cells. For example, it has been observed that endothelial colony forming cells align along the direction of the fibers present in electrospun scaffolds.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fioretta|first1=Emanuela S.|last2=Simonet|first2=Marc|last3=Smits|first3=Anthal I. P. M.|last4=Baaijens|first4=Frank P. T.|last5=Bouten|first5=Carlijn V. C.|title=Differential Response of Endothelial and Endothelial Colony Forming Cells on Electrospun Scaffolds with Distinct Microfiber Diameters|journal=Biomacromolecules|date=10 March 2014|volume=15|issue=3|pages=821–829|doi=10.1021/bm4016418}}</ref> Similarly, it has been demonstrated that the collagen fibers present in collagen gels and soft tissues can influence cell alignment, providing the most important stimulus in terms of cell orientation <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Foolen|first1=Jasper|last2=Deshpande|first2=Vikram S.|last3=Kanters|first3=Frans M. W.|last4=Baaijens|first4=Frank P. T.|title=The influence of matrix integrity on stress-fiber remodeling in 3D|journal=Biomaterials|date=1 October 2012|volume=33|issue=30|pages=7508–7518|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2012.06.103|pmid=22818650|issn=1878-5905}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=de Jonge|first1=Nicky|last2=Kanters|first2=Frans M. W.|last3=Baaijens|first3=Frank P. T.|last4=Bouten|first4=Carlijn V. C.|title=Strain-induced Collagen Organization at the Micro-level in Fibrin-based Engineered Tissue Constructs|journal=Annals of Biomedical Engineering|date=27 November 2012|volume=41|issue=4|pages=763–774|doi=10.1007/s10439-012-0704-3|pmid=23184346}}</ref>

==Potential of contact guidance for tissue engineering==
Recent research has highlighted the importance of cellular alignment for the mechanical properties and functionality of the prostheses developed using the principles of tissue engineering. Currently, scientists are investigating the mechanisms and potential of contact guidance to control cellular alignment, which would ultimately lead to the control of their cellular forces and certain aspects of collagen remodeling.

==Biological mechanisms determining contact guidance==
Many researchers have formulated hypotheses on the biological mechanisms determining contact guidance. In general, cellular contraction, stress fibers and focal adhesions seem to play an important role.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barocas|first1=V. H.|last2=Tranquillo|first2=R. T.|title=An Anisotropic Biphasic Theory of Tissue-Equivalent Mechanics: The Interplay Among Cell Traction, Fibrillar Network Deformation, Fibril Alignment, and Cell Contact Guidance|journal=Journal of Biomechanical Engineering|date=1997|volume=119|issue=2|pages=137|doi=10.1115/1.2796072}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vigliotti|first1=A.|last2=McMeeking|first2=R. M.|last3=Deshpande|first3=V. S.|title=Simulation of the cytoskeletal response of cells on grooved or patterned substrates|journal=Journal of The Royal Society Interface|date=11 March 2015|volume=12|issue=105|pages=20141320–20141320|doi=10.1098/rsif.2014.1320|pmc=4387521}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhou|first1=Feng|last2=Yuan|first2=Lin|last3=Huang|first3=He|last4=Chen|first4=Hong|title=Phenomenon of "contact guidance" on the surface with nano-micro-groove-like pattern and cell physiological effects|journal=Chinese Science Bulletin|date=13 September 2009|volume=54|issue=18|pages=3200–3205|doi=10.1007/s11434-009-0366-1}}</ref> Recently, a computational model has been developed that is able to simulate the re-alignment of cells and stress fibers on top of grooved surfaces.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vigliotti|first1=A.|last2=McMeeking|first2=R. M.|last3=Deshpande|first3=V. S.|title=Simulation of the cytoskeletal response of cells on grooved or patterned substrates|journal=Journal of The Royal Society Interface|date=11 March 2015|volume=12|issue=105|pages=20141320–20141320|doi=10.1098/rsif.2014.1320|pmc=4387521}}</ref> Briefly, it has been supposed that cells, once seeded, form focal adhesions on top of the ridges and not above the grooves. Once formed, the focal adhesions produce a signal that starts to diffuse into the cell inducing stress fiber assembly. At this point, there are two different possibilities, depending on the groove size. On the one hand, when the groove size is small, the intracellular signal produced by focal adhesions on the ridges can homogenously reach all locations in the cell. In that case, the stress fiber assembly is isotropic, and these fibers can pull on their surroundings in an isotropic fashion, and consequently the resulting cell shape is isotropic (without a preferred alignment). On the other hand, when the groove size is relatively large, the intracellular signal cannot reach the locations of the cell situated on top of the grooves, as diffusion is limited. As a result, stress fibers form only close to the ridges, and these acto-myosin bundles pull on their surroundings anisotropically. Due to the anisotropic cellular contraction, stress fibers and cells align along the direction of the microgrooves. Further experiments are necessary to validate this theory.

