{{unreferenced|date=March 2017}} [[File:Nasa-hi-air-pr-avg.png|right|]] The '''North Pacific High''' is a semi-permanent, [[subtropic|subtropical]] [[anticyclone]] located in the northeastern portion of the [[Pacific Ocean]], located northeast of [[Hawaii]] and west of [[California]]. It is strongest during the northern hemisphere summer and shifts towards the equator during the winter, when the [[Aleutian Low]] becomes more active. It is responsible for California's typically dry [[summer]] and [[autumn|fall]] and typically wet [[winter]] and [[spring (season)|spring]], as well as Hawaii's year-round [[trade winds]].
